  "id": "MAL-2026-5422",
  "summary": "Malicious code in @nstrlabs/shared-components (npm)",
  "details": "\n---\n_-= Per source details. Do not edit below this line.=-_\n\n## Source: amazon-inspector (af9737388d5d3e4542198eb5ae3bb13c2d13eefc97331fb32ed105626218776a)\n@nstrlabs/shared-components 99.0.1 ships a preinstall hook (package.json scripts.preinstall runs index.js) that automatically fires on `npm install`. index.js collects os.hostname(), os.userInfo().username, __dirname, and process.cwd(), then exfiltrates them two ways: (1) hex-encoded as DNS labels under a `*.oast.live` subdomain (Interactsh-style out-of-band channel) via dns.resolve, and (2) as a JSON POST over plain HTTP to the bare IP 172.201.213.59:9090/c. The package name (`@nstrlabs/shared-components`), inflated version (99.0.1), and self-described 'security research' purpose match the canonical dependency-confusion probe shape: any internal build pipeline that resolves `@nstrlabs/*` from the public registry will silently leak host identifiers to attacker-controlled infrastructure.\n",
